%N A257240 Decimal expansion of the real root of x^3 - 3*x - 10.
%C A257240 This is related to the fourth of thirty problems posed by Niccolò Tartaglia to Antonio Maria Fiore in the year 1535 (in Venice it was still 1534). See the Katscher reference [in German] pp. 14, 15.
%C A257240 The problem is: find me a number which when 3 of its cubic roots are subtracted leaves 10. That is z - 3*z^(1/3) = 10, or, with z = x^3, x^3 - 3*x = 10, with real solution x1. The solution to the problem is then z1 = x1^3 = 13 - 4*x1 (see the example section).
%D A257240 Friedrich Katscher, Die Kubischen Gleichungen bei Nicolo Tartaglia, Verlag der Österreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften, 2001, Wien, Aufgabe XXV, pp. 13-16.
%H A257240 MacTutor History of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Tartaglia/">Niccolò Tartaglia</a>.
%H A257240 <a href="/index/Al#algebraic_03">Index entries for algebraic numbers, degree 3</a>
%F A257240 The real solution x1 to x^3 - 3*x - 10 = 0 is x1 = (5 + 2*sqrt(6))^(1/3) + (5 - 2*sqrt(6))^(1/3).
%F A257240 The two complex solutions are a + b*i and a - b*i, with a = -x1/2 and b = sqrt(3)*y1/2 where y1 = (5 + 2*sqrt(6))^(1/3) - (5 - 2*sqrt(6))^(1/3).
%e A257240 x1 = 2.6128878647175447544072499386297629...
%e A257240 y1 = 1.6814229074174677895820170587695490...
%e A257240 z1 = 17.8386635941526342632217498158892887...
